        .col-lg-8

          // TL;DR
          .card.border-0.bg-light.p-4.mb-4
            h5.fw-bold TL;DR / Key Takeaways
            ul.mb-0
              li
                strong Hour-by-Hour Timeline:
                |  Withdrawal symptoms typically begin 6–12 hours after your last drink and peak around 12–24 hours.
              li
                strong Physical Symptoms:
                |  Expect anxiety, tremors, sweating, nausea, elevated heart rate, and insomnia during the first 24 hours without alcohol.
              li
                strong Danger Zone:
                |  Severe withdrawal (seizures, hallucinations, delirium tremens) can be life-threatening. Heavy daily drinkers should never detox alone.
              li
                strong Good News:
                |  For many people, the worst of acute withdrawal passes within 72 hours, and your body begins healing almost immediately.
              li
                strong Spokane Help:
                |  Free medical detox, peer support, and crisis resources are available right now in Spokane—no insurance required.

          // Quick Definition
          h2.mt-2 Quick Definition
          p.lead
            strong The first 24 hours without alcohol
            |  refers to the initial phase of alcohol cessation during which the body begins to recalibrate after removing a central nervous system depressant. Depending on drinking history, this period may involve mild discomfort or medically significant withdrawal symptoms requiring professional supervision.

          // Table of Contents
          .mb-5.p-4.bg-light.rounded
            h4.h5 Table of Contents
            ul.list-unstyled.mb-0
              li.mb-2: a(href="#why-it-matters") Why the First 24 Hours Without Alcohol Matter
              li.mb-2: a(href="#who-this-is-for") Who This Guide Is For
              li.mb-2: a(href="#timeline") Hour-by-Hour Timeline: What to Expect
              li.mb-2: a(href="#best-practices") Best Practices That Actually Help You Survive Day One
              li.mb-2: a(href="#comparison") Mild vs. Moderate vs. Severe Withdrawal
              li.mb-2: a(href="#mistakes") Common Mistakes (and How to Avoid Them)
              li.mb-2: a(href="#faq") Frequently Asked Questions
              li.mb-0: a(href="#conclusion") Your First 24 Hours Start Now

          hr.my-5

          // Section 1: Why It Matters
          h2#why-it-matters
            i.bi.bi-lightning-charge.text-primary.me-2
            | Why the First 24 Hours Without Alcohol Matter

          p Understanding what happens in the **first 24 hours without alcohol** is not about scaring you—it is about removing the fear of the unknown. When you know exactly what your body will do at hour 6, hour 12, and hour 20, you stop interpreting normal withdrawal symptoms as a sign that something is catastrophically wrong.

          p This matters for two critical reasons:

          ul
            li
              strong Safety:
              |  Alcohol is one of only two substances (along with benzodiazepines) where withdrawal can be fatal. Knowing the red flags could save your life.
            li
              strong Confidence:
              |  When you understand the timeline, every passing hour becomes proof that you are getting closer to the other side—not falling apart.

          p According to the
            a(href="https://www.niaaa.nih.gov/publications/brochures-and-fact-sheets/understanding-alcohol-use-disorder" target="_blank" rel="noopener")  National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism (NIAAA)
            | , approximately 29.5 million Americans ages 12 and older had Alcohol Use Disorder in 2021. Many of them faced (or will face) this exact first day. You are not alone.

          p If you are already wondering whether your relationship with alcohol has crossed a line, our guide on
            a(href="/blog/am-i-an-alcoholic-signs.html")  15 honest signs of alcoholism
            |  can help you assess where you stand before you begin.

          hr.my-5

          // Who This Is For
          h2#who-this-is-for
            i.bi.bi-people.text-primary.me-2
            | Who This Guide Is For

          p This guide is designed for anyone approaching their first full day without alcohol and wanting to know what to expect. Specifically:

          ul
            li
              strong The person on Day Zero:
              |  You had your last drink tonight (or plan to), and you want a map of what is coming.
            li
              strong The concerned loved one:
              |  Your partner, child, or friend is quitting, and you need to know what warning signs to watch for.
            li
              strong The "restart" veteran:
              |  You have been through Day 1 before but never with a clear, detailed plan. This time will be different.
            li
              strong The medical professional or peer counselor:
              |  You want a straightforward, patient-friendly handout for someone about to attempt sobriety.

          .card.border-0.bg-warning.bg-opacity-10.p-4.mb-4
            h5.fw-bold
              i.bi.bi-exclamation-triangle.text-warning.me-2
              | Medical Disclaimer
            p.mb-0 This article is for educational purposes only and does not replace medical advice. If you are a heavy daily drinker or have a history of seizures, hallucinations, or delirium tremens, 
              strong do not attempt to detox without medical supervision.
              |  Call 911 or go to your nearest emergency room.

          hr.my-5

          // Hour-by-Hour Timeline
          h2#timeline
            i.bi.bi-clock-history.text-primary.me-2
            | Hour-by-Hour: The First 24 Hours Without Alcohol

          p Every body is different, and the severity of your symptoms depends on how much, how often, and how long you have been drinking. The timeline below reflects a typical experience for someone with moderate-to-heavy daily alcohol use.

          // Hour 0-2
          h3 Hours 0–2: The Calm Before the Storm
          p
            strong What to expect:
            |  In the first couple of hours after your last drink, you likely feel normal or even relieved. The alcohol is still being metabolized by your liver, and your blood alcohol content (BAC) is declining slowly.
          p
            strong What is happening inside:
            |  Your liver is working overtime processing ethanol. Your brain, which has been suppressed by alcohol's depressant effects, has not yet realized the supply is being cut off.
          p
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  Use this window to prepare. Hydrate with water and electrolytes. Remove all alcohol from your home. Tell someone you trust what you are doing.
          p
            strong Common Pitfall:
            |  Feeling "fine" and convincing yourself that quitting will be easy—or unnecessary. This calm is temporary.

          // Hour 3-6
          h3 Hours 3–6: The First Signals
          p
            strong What to expect:
            |  Mild anxiety begins creeping in. You may notice restlessness, slight irritability, or a vague sense of unease. Some people describe it as feeling like they have had too much coffee.
          p
            strong What is happening inside:
            |  Your central nervous system (CNS) is starting to notice the absence of alcohol's depressant effect. Your brain has been producing extra stimulatory neurotransmitters (glutamate) to counterbalance alcohol's daily presence. Without alcohol to dampen them, those neurotransmitters are starting to fire unopposed.
          p
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  Start a simple, repetitive activity—walking, cleaning, organizing. Physical movement helps burn off the excess nervous energy.
          p
            strong Common Pitfall:
            |  Reaching for caffeine. Your CNS is already overstimulated; coffee will make anxiety and tremors worse.

          // Hour 6-12
          h3 Hours 6–12: Symptoms Become Undeniable
          p
            strong What to expect:
            |  This is where most people first feel genuine discomfort. Common symptoms include:
          ul
            li Hand tremors (shaky hands when reaching for a glass of water)
            li Noticeable sweating, even in a cool room
            li Nausea or upset stomach
            li Elevated heart rate (you can feel your pulse)
            li Increased anxiety or a feeling of "impending doom"
            li Headache
          p
            strong What is happening inside:
            |  Your autonomic nervous system is now in overdrive. The brain's "accelerator" (excitatory neurotransmitters) is floored, and the "brake" (alcohol) has been removed. This neurochemical imbalance is the engine behind every withdrawal symptom you feel.
          p
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  If tremors are visible or your resting heart rate exceeds 100 bpm, call a medical professional. These are clinical signs that withdrawal is escalating.
          p
            strong Common Pitfall:
            |  Thinking "one drink will take the edge off." It will—for about 45 minutes. Then the cycle resets and the next withdrawal attempt becomes harder.

          // Hour 12-18
          h3 Hours 12–18: The Peak Begins
          p
            strong What to expect:
            |  For many people, this window is the most physically uncomfortable part of the first 24 hours. Symptoms intensify:
          ul
            li Tremors may spread from hands to arms
            li Insomnia or an inability to rest, despite exhaustion
            li Profuse sweating and clammy skin
            li Mood swings—anger, sadness, and anxiety can cycle rapidly
            li Some people experience mild auditory or visual disturbances (hearing things that are not there, seeing shadows move)
          p
            strong What is happening inside:
            |  Your sympathetic nervous system ("fight or flight") is fully activated. Cortisol and adrenaline are flooding your system. Your body is essentially in survival mode, responding to the chemical crisis caused by the sudden absence of a depressant it had adapted to.
          p
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  This is the moment to lean on your support system. Call a sober friend, attend an AA meeting, or call the SAMHSA National Helpline at 1-800-662-4357. You do not have to do this alone.
          p
            strong Common Pitfall:
            |  Isolating yourself. The combination of shame and physical misery makes you want to hide. Fight that instinct—isolation is the most dangerous place to be right now.

          // Hour 18-24
          h3 Hours 18–24: You Are in the Fight
          p
            strong What to expect:
            |  Symptoms may plateau or continue to intensify depending on your drinking history. At this stage:
          ul
            li Anxiety and agitation remain high
            li Tremors continue but may begin to stabilize for mild-to-moderate cases
            li Sleep deprivation begins to compound irritability
            li Cravings may peak—your brain desperately wants the "fix" it has been trained to expect
            li
              strong Danger:
              |  In severe cases, seizures can occur, typically 12–48 hours after the last drink. This is a medical emergency.
          p
            strong What is happening inside:
            |  Your brain is in full neurochemical rebellion. However, for those with mild-to-moderate withdrawal, your body is beginning to establish a new equilibrium. Every hour that passes without alcohol is an hour of literal neurological healing.
          p
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  Focus on small victories. You have made it 24 hours. That is extraordinary. Document how you feel right now so you remember the cost if you ever think about going back.
          p
            strong Common Pitfall:
            |  Assuming you are "past the danger" at hour 24. Severe withdrawal symptoms (including delirium tremens) can emerge 48–72 hours after the last drink. Continue monitoring yourself or having someone check in on you.

          // Survival Checklist
          h3
            i.bi.bi-check2-square.text-success.me-2
            | First 24 Hours Survival Checklist

          .card.border-0.bg-light.p-4.mb-4
            ul.mb-0
              li ☐ Remove all alcohol from your home
              li ☐ Tell at least one person you trust
              li ☐ Stock up on water, electrolyte drinks (Pedialyte, Gatorade), and bland food
              li ☐ Have emergency contacts saved: 911 / SAMHSA Helpline (1-800-662-4357)
              li ☐ Set alarms every 4 hours to eat something small and hydrate
              li ☐ Prepare a distraction kit: movies, podcasts, books, puzzles
              li ☐ If you are a heavy daily drinker, arrange medical supervision or go to a detox facility
              li ☐ Download a sobriety tracking app (I Am Sober, Sober Time)
              li ☐ Write down your #1 reason for quitting and put it somewhere visible

          hr.my-5

          // Best Practices
          h2#best-practices
            i.bi.bi-star-fill.text-warning.me-2
            | Best Practices That Actually Help You Survive Day One

          p Most online advice about quitting alcohol is frustratingly generic. Here is what actually moves the needle in the first 24 hours, based on recovery community experience and clinical best practices.

          h3 1. Hydrate Aggressively, But Smartly
          p Alcohol is a diuretic—your body is dehydrated at a cellular level. But do not just chug water. Alternate between water and an electrolyte solution to replace the sodium, potassium, and magnesium your body has been depleting.

          h3 2. Eat, Even If You Do Not Want To
          p Nausea is common, but an empty stomach will make every other symptom worse. Aim for bland, carb-heavy foods: toast, crackers, bananas, rice. Small portions every 2–3 hours.

          h3 3. Control Your Environment
          p If your living room is where you usually drink, move to a different room. If your friends text about going out, mute the group chat for 24 hours. Environmental cues are the #1 trigger for relapse in the first day.

          h3 4. Use the "5-5-5" Grounding Technique for Anxiety
          p When panic hits: name 5 things you can see, 4 you can hear, 3 you can touch, 2 you can smell, and 1 you can taste. This neurological interrupt pulls your brain out of the anxiety spiral and into the present moment.

          h3 5. Do NOT Make Big Decisions
          p Your brain is in chemical chaos. This is not the day to call your ex, quit your job, or confront someone. Your only job today is to make it through.

          .card.border-0.border-start.border-primary.border-4.bg-light.p-4.mb-4
            h5.fw-bold
              i.bi.bi-chat-quote.text-primary.me-2
              | Expert Note
            p.mb-0.fst-italic "The first 24 hours are not about willpower. They are about physiology. Your brain is literally recalibrating its chemistry. Be as patient with yourself as you would be with someone recovering from surgery—because neurologically, it is not that different." — Recovery peer counselor, Spokane, WA

          hr.my-5

          // Example / Template
          h2
            i.bi.bi-journal-text.text-primary.me-2
            | Day One Plan: Copy-and-Paste Template

          p Use this template to structure your first 24 hours. Fill it out before your last drink or share it with a loved one who can help you follow it.

          .card.border-0.bg-light.p-4.mb-4
            pre.mb-0(style="white-space: pre-wrap; font-family: inherit;")
              | MY FIRST 24-HOUR PLAN
              |
              | Date of Last Drink: _______________
              | Time of Last Drink: _______________
              |
              | My #1 Reason for Quitting:
              | _______________________________________________
              |
              | Emergency Contact 1: _____________ (Phone: ___________)
              | Emergency Contact 2: _____________ (Phone: ___________)
              |
              | ER to go to if symptoms get severe: _______________
              |
              | HOUR-BY-HOUR CHECK-IN:
              | [ ] Hour 6 — How do I feel? ________________________
              | [ ] Hour 12 — Symptoms? Heart rate? ________________
              | [ ] Hour 18 — Called my support person? _____________
              | [ ] Hour 24 — I MADE IT. Next step: ________________
              |
              | Supplies I Have Ready:
              | [ ] Water + Electrolytes
              | [ ] Bland food (toast, crackers, bananas)
              | [ ] Distraction kit (movies, books, puzzles)
              | [ ] Phone charged with emergency numbers saved
              |
              | Spokane Resources:
              | SAMHSA Helpline: 1-800-662-4357
              | WA Recovery Help Line: 1-866-789-1511
              | Get Sober Spokane: www.getsoberspokane.com

          hr.my-5

          // Comparison Table
          h2#comparison
            i.bi.bi-table.text-primary.me-2
            | Mild vs. Moderate vs. Severe Alcohol Withdrawal

          p Not everyone experiences the first 24 hours the same way. The comparison below helps you identify where you or your loved one may fall on the withdrawal spectrum.

          .table-responsive.mt-4
            table.table.table-bordered.bg-white
              thead.bg-light
                tr
                  th Feature
                  th Mild Withdrawal
                  th Moderate Withdrawal
                  th Severe Withdrawal
              tbody
                tr
                  td **Typical Drinker Profile**
                  td Social/occasional heavy drinker
                  td Daily drinker, several drinks/day
                  td Long-term heavy drinker (years)
                tr
                  td **Onset**
                  td 6–12 hours
                  td 6–12 hours
                  td 6–24 hours
                tr
                  td **Primary Symptoms**
                  td Anxiety, mild tremor, insomnia
                  td Sweating, nausea, visible tremors, rapid pulse
                  td Seizures, hallucinations, delirium tremens
                tr
                  td **Risk Level**
                  td Low – manageable at home with support
                  td Moderate – medical evaluation recommended
                  td HIGH – medical emergency, inpatient detox required
                tr
                  td **Recommended Setting**
                  td Home with a sober buddy
                  td Outpatient medical supervision
                  td Hospital or inpatient detox facility
                tr
                  td **Duration of Acute Phase**
                  td 24–48 hours
                  td 48–72 hours
                  td 3–7+ days
                tr
                  td **Medication Likely?**
                  td Rarely
                  td Often (benzodiazepines, anti-nausea)
                  td Almost always

          p If you believe you fall into the moderate or severe category, Spokane has
            a(href="/blog/free-addiction-help-spokane.html")  free addiction treatment resources
            |  that can connect you with medical detox at no cost through Apple Health (Medicaid).

          hr.my-5

          // Common Mistakes
          h2#mistakes
            i.bi.bi-x-octagon-fill.text-danger.me-2
            | Common Mistakes in the First 24 Hours (and How to Avoid Them)

          ol.mt-4
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Quitting cold turkey without a medical assessment.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  If you drink daily, see a doctor #[em before] your last drink. A quick evaluation can determine whether you need medication-assisted detox. Learn about
              a(href="/blog/medication-assisted-treatment-spokane.html")  medication-assisted treatment in Spokane
              | .
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Telling no one what you are doing.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Withdrawal can be medically dangerous. At minimum, tell one person who can check on you every few hours.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Relying on willpower alone.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Willpower is not a medical intervention. Structure your environment: remove alcohol, avoid triggers, have a physical plan (food, water, distractions).
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Substituting with other substances.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Swapping alcohol for cannabis, benzodiazepines (without a prescription), or other drugs creates a new dependency. If you need anxiety relief, call a medical provider.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Assuming the worst is over at hour 24.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Peak withdrawal symptoms often hit between 24–72 hours. Delirium tremens can appear at 48–96 hours. Stay vigilant through at least day three.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Not having a "what's next" plan.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Day 1 is just the door. Without a recovery plan for days 2–30 (meetings, counseling, peer support), the relapse rate skyrockets. Check our
              a(href="/blog/aa-na-meetings-spokane.html")  Spokane AA & NA meetings guide
              |  to line up community support.

          hr.my-5

          // FAQ
          h2#faq.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-question-circle.text-primary.me-2
            | Frequently Asked Questions

