                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqCollapse3" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqCollapse3")
                  | Is it safe to quit drinking cold turkey?
              #faqCollapse3.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqHeading3" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | For light or moderate drinkers, quitting abruptly is generally safe. However, if you drink daily or heavily, quitting cold turkey can trigger dangerous withdrawal symptoms. Medical detox is strongly recommended for heavy, chronic drinkers.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqHeading4
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqCollapse4" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqCollapse4")
                  | What does alcohol withdrawal feel like?
              #faqCollapse4.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqHeading4" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Most people describe the first 24 hours as an intense combination of anxiety, restlessness, sweating, nausea, and irritability. Some experience hand tremors, rapid heartbeat, and difficulty sleeping. The severity varies based on drinking history.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqHeading5
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqCollapse5" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqCollapse5")
                  | Should I go to the ER for alcohol withdrawal?
              #faqCollapse5.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqHeading5" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Go to the ER immediately if you experience seizures, hallucinations, a fever above 101°F, severe confusion, or uncontrollable vomiting. These are signs of severe withdrawal that require emergency medical intervention.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqHeading6
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqCollapse6" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqCollapse6")
                  | What helps with alcohol withdrawal symptoms at home?
              #faqCollapse6.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqHeading6" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | For mild withdrawal, hydration, electrolyte drinks, light nutritious meals, and rest can help. However, home detox should only be attempted for mild cases and ideally with someone monitoring you. Severe withdrawal always requires medical care.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqHeading7
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqCollapse7" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqCollapse7")
                  | Does everyone experience alcohol withdrawal?
              #faqCollapse7.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqHeading7" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | No. Withdrawal severity depends on the duration and intensity of drinking. Occasional or light social drinkers typically experience little to no withdrawal. Daily heavy drinkers and those with a long history of alcohol use are at highest risk for significant symptoms.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqHeading8
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqCollapse8" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqCollapse8")
                  | Where can I get help for alcohol withdrawal in Spokane?
              #faqCollapse8.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqHeading8" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Spokane has multiple free and low-cost resources including medical detox through Apple Health (Medicaid), TRIUMPH Treatment Services, Frontier Behavioral Health, and the
                  a(href="https://www.samhsa.gov/find-help/national-helpline" target="_blank" rel="noopener")  SAMHSA National Helpline
                  |  at 1-800-662-4357. Visit our
                  a(href="/blog/free-addiction-help-spokane.html")  free addiction help guide
                  |  for the full list.

          hr.my-5

          // Conclusion + CTA
          h2#conclusion.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-sun.text-warning.me-2
            | Your First 24 Hours Without Alcohol Start Now

          p The **first 24 hours without alcohol** are going to be uncomfortable. There is no sugarcoating that. But they are also the most consequential hours of your recovery—because they are the ones where you prove to yourself that you can choose differently. Every symptom you endure is your body healing from something that was slowly destroying it. The anxiety, the tremors, the sleeplessness—they are not signs of weakness. They are signs of your nervous system coming back online without a chemical crutch.

          p You do not need to have a perfect plan. You do not need to have your whole life figured out. You just need to survive today, and Spokane has every resource you need to do that safely.

          p If you are in crisis right now, call **1-800-662-4357** (SAMHSA National Helpline, free and confidential, 24/7). If you want local, in-person support, start with our
            a(href="/blog/aa-na-meetings-spokane.html")  Spokane AA & NA meetings guide
            |  or
            a(href="/blog/free-addiction-help-spokane.html")  free addiction help resources
            | .

